45
00:01:53,520 --> 00:01:56,640
let's start with the problem. Digital

46
00:01:56,640 --> 00:01:59,360
identity today is borrowed. When you

47
00:01:59,360 --> 00:02:01,840
create an account, get a credential or

48
00:02:01,840 --> 00:02:03,840
receive a certificate. You don't

49
00:02:03,840 --> 00:02:07,840
actually own it. The issuer does, the

50
00:02:07,840 --> 00:02:11,520
registry does, or the platform does. And

51
00:02:11,520 --> 00:02:14,080
if that platform shuts down, that

52
00:02:14,080 --> 00:02:17,040
registry gets compromised or that issuer

53
00:02:17,040 --> 00:02:19,440
revokes access, your identity

54
00:02:19,440 --> 00:02:22,319
effectively disappears with it.

55
00:02:22,319 --> 00:02:25,040
You are effectively a tenant, not an

56
00:02:25,040 --> 00:02:28,000
owner of your digital identity. But

57
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:31,360
KERI changes this. With KERI, your

58
00:02:31,360 --> 00:02:33,519
identity is rooted in cryptographic keys

59
00:02:33,519 --> 00:02:37,519
that you control. No registry needed, no

60
00:02:37,519 --> 00:02:39,599
platform dependency.

61
00:02:39,599 --> 00:02:42,640
It's portable, verifiable,

62
00:02:42,640 --> 00:02:45,360
and it is yours.

63
00:02:45,360 --> 00:02:48,800
So what is KERI exactly?

64
00:02:48,800 --> 00:02:50,720
And I don't think anyone's actually said

65
00:02:50,720 --> 00:02:54,959
the acronym in the last few days.

66
00:02:54,959 --> 00:02:58,000
So KERI stands for key event receipt

67
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:00,560
infrastructure and there are three core

68
00:03:00,560 --> 00:03:03,680
concepts that make this work. The first

69
00:03:03,680 --> 00:03:06,959
is self-certifying identifiers

70
00:03:06,959 --> 00:03:08,640
and what this means is that your

71
00:03:08,640 --> 00:03:11,519
identifier is derived directly from your

72
00:03:11,519 --> 00:03:14,480
cryptographic keys. There is no registry

73
00:03:14,480 --> 00:03:16,720
or registrar that grants you your

74
00:03:16,720 --> 00:03:18,400
identity.

75
00:03:18,400 --> 00:03:20,879
The second concept is that every

76
00:03:20,879 --> 00:03:23,040
critical action you take with that

77
00:03:23,040 --> 00:03:26,000
identifier, such as creating it or

78
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:28,000
rotation those controlling cryptographic

79
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:30,879
keys, all of these critical events are

80
00:03:30,879 --> 00:03:35,360
signed and chained into a tamper-evident log.

81
00:03:35,360 --> 00:03:38,400
And the third concept is everyone can

82
00:03:38,400 --> 00:03:41,200
verify your identity by replaying the

83
00:03:41,200 --> 00:03:44,319
same tamper-evident log. There is no

84
00:03:44,319 --> 00:03:47,120
need for phone home to a central

85
00:03:47,120 --> 00:03:49,599
repository or authority. And if you'd

86
00:03:49,599 --> 00:03:51,920
like to understand a bit more about no

87
00:03:51,920 --> 00:03:53,840
phone home, I encourage you to visit to

88
00:03:53,840 --> 00:03:56,159
visit nophonehome.com

89
00:03:56,159 --> 00:03:58,879
and you can read a bit more about this.

90
00:03:58,879 --> 00:04:02,080
So this combination of concepts, this is

91
00:04:02,080 --> 00:04:04,080
what gives us something that no other

92
00:04:04,080 --> 00:04:06,640
identity system achieves and that is

93
00:04:06,640 --> 00:04:10,480
truly portable trust.

94
00:04:10,480 --> 00:04:12,480
So let's make this concrete. In KERI,

95
00:04:12,480 --> 00:04:14,560
your identifier is called an autonomic

96
00:04:14,560 --> 00:04:17,359
identifier or an AID. And this is a

97
00:04:17,359 --> 00:04:19,120
cryptographic identifier that you

98
00:04:19,120 --> 00:04:21,519
generate. Its authority comes from the

99
00:04:21,519 --> 00:04:24,800
keys that you made. And no one else or

100
00:04:24,800 --> 00:04:27,919
entity issues that to you. Every

101
00:04:27,919 --> 00:04:30,880
significant action that the AID conducts

102
00:04:30,880 --> 00:04:33,680
gets recorded in a Key Event Log and

103
00:04:33,680 --> 00:04:36,080
that is called a KEL.

104
00:04:36,080 --> 00:04:37,840
Your inception event, this is when you

105
00:04:37,840 --> 00:04:40,639
create your AID. The rotation events

106
00:04:40,639 --> 00:04:42,479
that change the AID's controlling

107
00:04:42,479 --> 00:04:45,040
cryptographic keys or interaction events

108
00:04:45,040 --> 00:04:46,800
that anchor data that is critical to

109
00:04:46,800 --> 00:04:49,759
your AID. Each and every event is

110
00:04:49,759 --> 00:04:54,310
cryptographically signed.

111
00:04:55,510 --> 00:04:57,360
Each and every event is
cryptographically signed with the

112
00:04:57,360 --> 00:04:59,440
previous one. And this is what creates a

113
00:04:59,440 --> 00:05:02,800
tamper-evident chain. If anyone alters a

114
00:05:02,800 --> 00:05:04,400
single event in this chain, the

115
00:05:04,400 --> 00:05:06,560
signatures break and the tampering is

116
00:05:06,560 --> 00:05:09,360
immediately detectable.

117
00:05:09,360 --> 00:05:10,880
If you're familiar with blockchain

118
00:05:10,880 --> 00:05:12,960
technology, this is the same hashchain

119
00:05:12,960 --> 00:05:15,440
data structure that makes blockchain

120
00:05:15,440 --> 00:05:19,360
secure or immutable.

121
00:05:19,360 --> 00:05:21,440
Now that you understand the foundations,

122
00:05:21,440 --> 00:05:23,440
AIDs and KELs, let's talk about the

123
00:05:23,440 --> 00:05:25,120
infrastructure that makes it all work at

124
00:05:25,120 --> 00:05:27,520
scale. And we've organized these into

125
00:05:27,520 --> 00:05:29,919
five roles. And conveniently, Sam has

126
00:05:29,919 --> 00:05:32,400
started them all with a letter W. So,

127
00:05:32,400 --> 00:05:35,120
let's move on to the wallet. And this is

128
00:05:35,120 --> 00:05:37,280
where your identity lives. It's the

129
00:05:37,280 --> 00:05:39,919
holder's home. The wallet generates and

130
00:05:39,919 --> 00:05:42,080
rotates the cryptographic keys. It

131
00:05:42,080 --> 00:05:44,479
stores the verifiable credentials. In

132
00:05:44,479 --> 00:05:46,800
KERI, these are known as ACDCs. We'll

133
00:05:46,800 --> 00:05:49,039
talk a bit about this later. The wallet

134
00:05:49,039 --> 00:05:51,199
signs, presentations, and interaction

135
00:05:51,199 --> 00:05:53,759
events. And it collects all of this and

136
00:05:53,759 --> 00:05:55,360
it combines all of this with device

137
00:05:55,360 --> 00:05:57,280
grade security. This includes

138
00:05:57,280 --> 00:05:59,759
biometrics, secure enclaves, and anything

139
00:05:59,759 --> 00:06:01,680
else that occurs on the hardware device

140
00:06:01,680 --> 00:06:04,479
itself. The key insights here are:

141
00:06:04,479 --> 00:06:06,319
the wallet is the only component that the

142
00:06:06,319 --> 00:06:09,039
holder directly controls. The vital

143
00:06:09,039 --> 00:06:11,360
functions of the wallet in KERI are key

144
00:06:11,360 --> 00:06:14,240
management and signing.

145
00:06:14,240 --> 00:06:16,080
At Veridian, we've built an open-source

146
00:06:16,080 --> 00:06:17,759
mobile-first KERI wallet that is

147
00:06:17,759 --> 00:06:19,680
production ready and available today.

148
00:06:19,680 --> 00:06:21,840
You can download that from the Apple iOS

149
00:06:21,840 --> 00:06:24,080
stores as well as Android Play Store.

150
00:06:24,080 --> 00:06:26,720
and it is also available on the privacy-preserving

151
00:06:26,720 --> 00:06:29,500
operating system Graphine OS.

152
00:06:29,500 --> 00:06:36,210
Witnesses are the second W in the 5W
framework.

153
00:06:36,800 --> 00:06:38,720
They are designated services that

154
00:06:38,720 --> 00:06:41,199
receive, sign, and republish your key

155
00:06:41,199 --> 00:06:43,600
events. You can think of these as

156
00:06:43,600 --> 00:06:46,800
notaries for your KEL.

157
00:06:46,800 --> 00:06:48,479
They give your event log a highly

158
00:06:48,479 --> 00:06:50,639
available home so verifiers can access

159
00:06:50,639 --> 00:06:53,280
it when your wallet is offline. They

160
00:06:53,280 --> 00:06:56,080
produce receipts that prove the specific

161
00:06:56,080 --> 00:06:58,800
event has been seen at a specific time.

162
00:06:58,800 --> 00:07:00,720
And through redundancy of these

163
00:07:00,720 --> 00:07:05,520
witnesses, we can resist censorship.

164
00:07:05,520 --> 00:07:08,639
Critically, you choose your witnesses.

165
00:07:08,639 --> 00:07:11,199
They are not selected or imposed by the

166
00:07:11,199 --> 00:07:14,319
system on you. And at Veridian, we operate

167
00:07:14,319 --> 00:07:16,800
witness pools that you can use directly

168
00:07:16,800 --> 00:07:18,639
or you can host yourself in your own

169
00:07:18,639 --> 00:07:21,280
infrastructure.

170
00:07:21,280 --> 00:07:24,560
The third W is the watcher.

171
00:07:24,560 --> 00:07:27,280
Watchers are independent observers. They

172
00:07:27,280 --> 00:07:30,000
are critical to KERI.

173
00:07:30,000 --> 00:07:33,039
Their job is to detect duplicity.

174
00:07:33,039 --> 00:07:35,680
Meaning: they catch anyone who is trying

175
00:07:35,680 --> 00:07:38,240
to present two conflicting versions of

176
00:07:38,240 --> 00:07:41,280
the same Key Event Log.

177
00:07:41,280 --> 00:07:43,680
This is KERI's answer to the double spend

178
00:07:43,680 --> 00:07:46,720
problem that you have in blockchain.

179
00:07:46,720 --> 00:07:49,520
But they do it for identity.

180
00:07:49,520 --> 00:07:51,520
Watchers give verifiers confidence that

181
00:07:51,520 --> 00:07:54,080
the state they are seeing is the latest

182
00:07:54,080 --> 00:07:56,960
legitimate state of an identifier.

183
00:07:56,960 --> 00:07:59,360
They run separately from issuers and

184
00:07:59,360 --> 00:08:01,919
holders which means they are truly

185
00:08:01,919 --> 00:08:04,639
independent.

186
00:08:04,639 --> 00:08:08,240
This is what turns 'trust me!' into 'check

187
00:08:08,240 --> 00:08:12,400
for yourself' or 'verify for yourself'. And

188
00:08:12,400 --> 00:08:14,160
at Veridian, we are deploying highly

189
00:08:14,160 --> 00:08:15,599
available watcher infrastructure

190
00:08:15,599 --> 00:08:17,120
services in the second half of this

191
00:08:17,120 --> 00:08:20,000
year. And I would be remiss if I did not

192
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:23,440
pay attention and show gratitude to the

193
00:08:23,440 --> 00:08:26,080
HealthKERI for releasing the watcher and

194
00:08:26,080 --> 00:08:34,550
wallets to open source.

195
00:08:37,509 --> 00:08:39,599
The fourth W is web.
This is the discovery and transport

196
00:08:39,599 --> 00:08:42,640
layer of KERI. This is how parties find

197
00:08:42,640 --> 00:08:44,959
one another and how they exchange events

198
00:08:44,959 --> 00:08:47,600
and credentials and they do so through

199
00:08:47,600 --> 00:08:50,560
something known as an OOBI. This is an

200
00:08:50,560 --> 00:08:53,200
out-of-band introduction. You can think of

201
00:08:53,200 --> 00:08:55,600
these as sharable links that bootstrap

202
00:08:55,600 --> 00:08:58,480
trust between parties.

203
00:08:58,480 --> 00:09:00,399
Effectively, these can also be assumed

204
00:09:00,399 --> 00:09:03,040
to be QR codes that establish an initial

205
00:09:03,040 --> 00:09:05,920
connection and from there mailboxes and

206
00:09:05,920 --> 00:09:07,839
endpoints handle the messaging moving

207
00:09:07,839 --> 00:09:10,560
forward. The design of KERI is

208
00:09:10,560 --> 00:09:12,959
transport agnostic.

209
00:09:12,959 --> 00:09:16,240
So today it runs over HTTP, but the

210
00:09:16,240 --> 00:09:18,480
protocol doesn't really care about the

211
00:09:18,480 --> 00:09:20,640
transport. It can run over Bluetooth,

212
00:09:20,640 --> 00:09:23,360
over NFC. In fact, it can run across

213
00:09:23,360 --> 00:09:24,880
anything.

214
00:09:24,880 --> 00:09:26,640
And it's interoperable across different

215
00:09:26,640 --> 00:09:30,560
wallets and agents.

216
00:09:30,560 --> 00:09:32,720
Veridian provides hosted endpoints and

217
00:09:32,720 --> 00:09:34,880
sandboxes from our data center in

218
00:09:34,880 --> 00:09:37,279
Switzerland, including infrastructure

219
00:09:37,279 --> 00:09:38,720
deployment guides for those that are

220
00:09:38,720 --> 00:09:42,389
interested in deploying.

221
00:09:47,350 --> 00:09:50,800
The fifth and final W, the wizard.
This is how we achieve one-click KERI.

222
00:09:50,800 --> 00:09:52,640
For example, the majority of users are

223
00:09:52,640 --> 00:09:54,880
not going to understand how to set their

224
00:09:54,880 --> 00:09:58,240
witness threshold. Wizards abstract

225
00:09:58,240 --> 00:10:00,320
low-level details of KERI and they

226
00:10:00,320 --> 00:10:02,560
provide suitable defaults that ensure we

227
00:10:02,560 --> 00:10:05,680
make KERI accessible but safe for

228
00:10:05,680 --> 00:10:07,279
users.

229
00:10:07,279 --> 00:10:09,680
For developers, we expose highlevel easy

230
00:10:09,680 --> 00:10:12,399
to understand APIs to build on. And in

231
00:10:12,399 --> 00:10:15,360
short, the wizard bridges the protocol

232
00:10:15,360 --> 00:10:19,519
to the product. Without KERI, sorry,

233
00:10:19,519 --> 00:10:24,389
without wizards, ...

234
00:10:26,710 --> 00:10:28,800
Yes, without Wizards, KERI is a
powerful protocol.

235
00:10:28,800 --> 00:10:31,440
With Wizards, KERI is a product that

236
00:10:31,440 --> 00:10:34,640
you can ship to market. And at Veridian,

237
00:10:34,640 --> 00:10:36,880
we offer one-click onboarding, witness

238
00:10:36,880 --> 00:10:38,800
selection, and automated schema

239
00:10:38,800 --> 00:10:40,800
discovery.

240
00:10:40,800 --> 00:10:44,480
Now, this is the whole picture.

241
00:10:44,480 --> 00:10:46,880
This is how they all fit together.

242
00:10:46,880 --> 00:10:48,720
Wallets hold the keys and credentials.

243
00:10:48,720 --> 00:10:51,440
Witnesses attest to events. Watchers

244
00:10:51,440 --> 00:10:54,079
verify integrity. Wizards orchestrate

245
00:10:54,079 --> 00:10:56,480
operations and the web connects them all

246
00:10:56,480 --> 00:10:59,440
and provides scalability. Each of these

247
00:10:59,440 --> 00:11:01,920
five roles are independently operated,

248
00:11:01,920 --> 00:11:04,399
independently verified and uniquely can

249
00:11:04,399 --> 00:11:07,920
be independently replaced.

250
00:11:07,920 --> 00:11:10,320
So that's the friendly overview. We're

251
00:11:10,320 --> 00:11:12,079
going to delve a little bit deeper and I

252
00:11:12,079 --> 00:11:14,000
want to cover four concepts that take

253
00:11:14,000 --> 00:11:16,160
KERI from an interesting protocol to a

254
00:11:16,160 --> 00:11:18,480
production grade infrastructure. And

255
00:11:18,480 --> 00:11:20,640
those four concepts are pre-rotation,

256
00:11:20,640 --> 00:11:23,120
delegation, multi-signature control,

257
00:11:23,120 --> 00:11:25,440
and ACDCs.

258
00:11:25,440 --> 00:11:27,680
So we'll start with pre-rotation. And

259
00:11:27,680 --> 00:11:29,920
this is one of KERI's most elegant

260
00:11:29,920 --> 00:11:32,959
concepts. In fact, it was probably the

261
00:11:32,959 --> 00:11:36,800
main concept that enabled me to

262
00:11:36,800 --> 00:11:38,480
influence the board of the Cardano

263
00:11:38,480 --> 00:11:40,880
Foundation to allow me to build on

264
00:11:40,880 --> 00:11:42,720
KERI.

265
00:11:42,720 --> 00:11:44,480
Pre-rotation,

266
00:11:44,480 --> 00:11:46,000
as I mentioned, is one of the most

267
00:11:46,000 --> 00:11:48,560
elegant concepts of KERI. At

268
00:11:48,560 --> 00:11:51,279
inception of an AID, the moment you

269
00:11:51,279 --> 00:11:53,519
create it, you don't just commit to your

270
00:11:53,519 --> 00:11:56,560
current keys. You also include a hash of

271
00:11:56,560 --> 00:12:00,240
your next-keys set. Those next keys stay

272
00:12:00,240 --> 00:12:01,920
offline.

273
00:12:01,920 --> 00:12:04,160
They remain unused

274
00:12:04,160 --> 00:12:06,720
only until you need to rotate your

275
00:12:06,720 --> 00:12:09,360
